 the dome is perfectly upright,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\frac{\pi}{2}$
\end_inset

,
 but at the top it's perfectly horizontal,
 so you get 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset

.
 I thought about taking the average of the angles,
 so like,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P=CA\cos^{3}\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $C=1$
\end_inset

 and knowing that the area of a half-dome is 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\frac{1}{2}\left(4\pi r^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 I get 
\begin_inset Formula $P=2\pi r^{2}\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)^{3}=\frac{\pi}{\sqrt{2}}r^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

